Additionally, list-initialization also provides a way to initialize objects with a list of values rather than a single value (which is why it is called “list-initialization”). We show an example of this in lesson16.2 -- Introduction to std::vector and list constructors.List-initialization disallows narrowing conversionsOne of the primary benefits of list-initialization for new C++ programmers is that “narrowing conversions” are disallowed. This means that if you try to list-initialize a variable using a value that the variable can not safely hold, the compiler is required to produce a diagnostic (compilation error or warning) to notify you. For example:int main()
{
